        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The Neptune Trojan 2006 RJ103 is a moving target. It must be observed when high in the sky (elevation &gt;30 deg). Other than that, we would like to stress that the object is observable during the entire observing period (either day or night) with a rather stable surface brightness.
There is therefore no time constraint other then the one given by
the elevation. IMPORTANTLY, we give here the RA and DEC (and PM RA and PM DEC) for a specific date but those coordinates should be updated at the time of the observations as this is a
moving target.

In order to constrain the albedo of the brightest (and presumably) largest Neptune Trojan 2006 RJ103, we need to observe its thermal flux in one band (350 GHz). Assuming two different albedos (A=0.05 and A=0.20) that cover well the albedo range observed for other outer solar system small bodies (e.g. Centaurs, Jupiter Trojans, TNOs), we predict the following fluxes in band 7:
- ~0.29 mJy (A=0.05); rms=0.058 mJy
- ~0.069 mJy (A=0.20); rms=0.014 mJy

To constrain the albedo with a 25% error will require an rms of 20% in band 7.
This level will be achieved in ~3.9h on source in the worst case, that is assuming an albedo A=0.20 and thus a flux of 0.069 mJy and a rms of 0.014 mJy. If the albedo turns out to be lower (e.g., A=0.05), the source would be brighter (the flux would be 0.29 mJy instead of 0.069 mJy), ~3.9h of total integration time on source will allow us to achieve an albedo measurement with a ~5% error.


In conclusion, we request a sensitivity of 0.014 mJy on source in order to measure the albedo of the brightest (and presumably largest)  Neptune Trojan 2006 RJ103 with a precision equal to or better than 25%.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
