    <prp:abstract>Neptune Trojans (NTs), the most recently discovered small-body population of the solar system, are swarms of objects that lead/trail planet Neptune during its revolutions around the Sun. Observations indicate that NTs form a thick cloud of objects with a population perhaps ~10 times more numerous than that of Jupiter Trojans. As of today, we have very limited information concerning the physical properties of Neptune Trojans (optical colors for only 4 objects).  Here we propose to continue the reconnaissance and characterization of the physical properties of this population by obtaining the first albedo measurement of a Neptune Trojan (2006 RJ103). This measurement will give a very first element of answer concerning the origin of this population and its link with other population of outer solar system small bodies. Ultimatley, a proper characterization of the albedo distribution of Neptune Trojans will provide key constraints on the early dynamical evolution of the solar system.</prp:abstract>
